   <mods:abstract>Vally Weigl was an Austrian-American composer who lived from 1894-1982. She and her husband Karl Weigl, also a composer, fled Vienna in 1938 after the Nazi annexation of Austria due to their Jewish heritage. The Weigls were aided as refugees by the Quakers; upon arriving in America, the Weigls converted to the Quaker faith, and Vally in particular spent the rest of her life working tirelessly towards the Quaker goals of peace, equality, and tolerance. Vally believed in the power of music to make the world a better place and lived out this value in her work as a music therapist, political activist, and composer of pacifist music. This treatise seeks to introduce Vally's music to a wider audience as she remains widely unknown to twenty-first century musicians. A comprehensive biography shows how Vally overcame numerous challenges, often by turning to music and its healing, communicative, and professional facilities. A literature review explains how the author found primary and secondary source information on a composer about whom little has been written or published. The pacifist views Vally embraced in the later part of her life became central to her musical work as a concert organizer, composer, and performer. This treatise examines a number of Vally's politically involved compositions she wrote for choir or vocal chamber ensemble as well as Vally's other activist work with various Quaker and pacifist organizations.</mods:abstract>
